<subSubSection id="9983A9D91B10FFDCFA1FFF95F6DFFB78" pageId="14" pageNumber="525" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="D126FA521B10FFDCFA1FFF95F6DFFB78" blockId="14.[1414,2626,287,1269]" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">
<emphasis id="E3ED26401B10FFDCFA1FFF95F97AFBD9" bold="true" box="[1419,1770,996,1029]" pageId="14" pageNumber="525">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Data Deficient on The IUCN Red List. The Coyhaique Tuco-tuco was first reported by M. H. Gallardo and colleagues in 1996 to be an example of loss of genetic variation after the eruption of Hudson Volcano in southern Chile in 1991. Mean heterozygosity pre-eruption was 7-2% and decreased after eruption to 1-:3%, as well as the polymorphism and the number ofalleles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
